{{Infobox person |name= Gilbert Price |image= |birth_date={{birth date|1942|9|10}} |birth_place=[[New York City, New York]], U.S. |death_date= January 2, 1991 (age 48) |death_place=[[Vienna|Vienna, Austria]] |occupation=[[Theatre|Stage]], [[film]], [[television]] [[actor]] |awards= {{Plainlist| * [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical]] nominee (1972) * [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical]] nominee (1975) * [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]] nominee (1978) * [[Theatre World Award]] (1964) }} }}
'''Gilbert Price''' (September 10, 1942 – January 2, 1991) was an [[United States|American]] operatic [[baritone]] and actor.
Price was a [[Mentorship|protégé]] of [[Langston Hughes]].<ref name=NYarchive/> He was a life member of New York's famed [[Actors Studio]].<ref>{{cite book|quote=|first=David |last=Garfield|title=A Player's Place: The Story of The Actors Studio|year=1980|publisher=MacMillan Publishing Co., Inc.|location=New York|isbn=0-02-542650-8|page=279|chapter=Appendix: Life Members of The Actors Studio as of January 1980}}</ref> Price first gained notice in 1964, for his performances in Hughes' [[Off-Broadway]] production of ''[[Jerico-Jim Crow]].'' For his work, Price received a [[Theatre World Award]].<ref name=obituary>{{cite news|title=Gilbert Price, 48, Broadway Baritone|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/01/08/obituaries/gilbert-price-48-broadway-baritone.html|accessdate=June 11, 2012|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 8, 1991}}</ref>
==Early life== Price was born on September 10, 1942, in [[New York City]] of [[African-American]] heritage. In 1960, he graduated from [[Erasmus Hall High School]], where he stood out for both his talent and gentle, easygoing manner.<ref name=obituary/> It has been written that while he was a protégé of Langston Hughes, Hughes had become smitten with the young Price.<ref>Rampersad, Arnold. [https://books.google.com/books?id=qclO9rdN1XIC&pg=PA372&lpg=PA372&dq=gilbert+price+langston+hughes&source=bl&ots=CAvWgZMxDS&sig=6grHdCKEkQjYO8yAH-wN2nnrCD8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=FCPWT7miHsLl6QHIse2JAw&ved=0CFgQ6AEwAzgK#v=onepage&q=gilbert%20price%20langston%20hughes&f=false ''The Life of Langston Hughes: 1941-1967, I Dream a World'']. Vol. 2, p. 373. ''[[New York City|New York]]: [[Oxford University Press]]'', 1988. Retrieved June 11, 2012.</ref> Unpublished love poems by Hughes were addressed to a man Hughes called ''Beauty''; it has been posited these poems referred to Price.<ref name=NYarchive/><ref>{{cite web|title=Langston Hughes (1902-1967) Poet|url=http://www.uis.edu/lgbtq/LangstonHughes.html|publisher=''[[University of Illinois at Springfield]]''|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>
==Career== Price made guest appearances on several television talk and variety shows including ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', [[Red Skelton]], [[Garry Moore]] and ''[[The Merv Griffin Show]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ed Sullivan Show performance: I've Gotta be Me!|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ALDHD_qMwnw|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref> Price also sang [[oratorio]]s, including [[Mass (Bernstein)|Leonard Bernstein's Mass]], in 1971.
==Awards== Price was nominated for three [[Tony Award]]s and was the recipient of a [[Theatre World Award]]:<ref>{{cite web|title=Gilbert Price Tony Awards Info - Browse by Nominee|url=http://broadwayworld.com/tonyawardspersoninfo.php?nomname=Gilbert%2520Price|publisher=broadwayworld.com|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref><ref>[http://www.theatreworldawards.org/past-recipients.html Theatre World Award Recipients] Theatre World Awards; retrieved November 22, 2014.</ref> * ''[[Jerico-Jim Crow]]'' (1964) – Theatre World Award * ''[[Lost in the Stars]]'' (1972) – [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical]] * ''[[The Night That Made America Famous]]'' (1975) – [[Tony Award for Best Featured Actor in a Musical]] * ''[[Timbuktu!]]'' (1978) – [[Tony Award for Best Actor in a Musical]]
==Other works== * ''Fly Blackbird'' (1962) - [[C. Bernard Jackson]] & James Hatch * ''[[The Roar of the Greasepaint – The Smell of the Crowd]]'' (1965) - [[Leslie Bricusse]] & [[Anthony Newley]] * ''Promenade'' (1969) - [[Maria Irene Fornes]] & [[Al Carmines]] * ''[[1600 Pennsylvania Avenue (musical)|1600 Pennsylvania Avenue]]'' (1976) - [[Leonard Bernstein]] & [[Alan Jay Lerner]]
==Death== Price died in [[Vienna|Vienna, Austria]], in 1991 of accidental [[asphyxia]]tion. He was 48 years old.<ref name=NYarchive>{{cite web|title=Gilbert Price collection, 1965-1991.|url=http://www.nypl.org/archives/4123|publisher=''[[New York Public Library]] archive''|accessdate=June 11, 2012}}</ref>
