{{Other people|Richard Roberts}} {{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} '''Richard Roberts''' (1803–1841) was an Irish sea captain. He entered the [[Royal Navy]] in his youth and served with them until he gained the rank of Lieutenant, and was given command of the [[SS Sirius (1837)|SS ''Sirius'']]. With Roberts at the helm, the ''Sirius'' became the first steamship to travel across the Atlantic to America, in April 1838. Shortly afterward, he was transferred to the [[SS President|SS ''President'']], which was lost at sea in March 1841. Roberts is presumed to have gone down with the ship.<ref>{{cite book |last=Windele |first=J. |year=1846 |url=http://www.corkpastandpresent.ie/history/windelescork/Windele_ed.pdf |title=Historical And Descriptive Notices Of The City Of Cork And Its Vicinity; Gougaun-Barra, Glengariff, And Killarney |page=158}}</ref>
Roberts loved the sea so, that he's quoted as saying "..I'd go to sea in a bath tub[washing-tub]".<ref>Great Ocean Liners, PBS television, c.1993</ref>
